Input:When I wake up and start to breathe my lungs fill up with air. As air moves in, the air pressure inside me will decrease by a tiny amount (1 kPa). This pressure difference will cause air inside the lungs to escape through lung tissue and alveoli which open up to allow outflow.
Breathing is a balancing act: If I keep breathing too much the lungs might start collapsing. But, if I don't breathe deeply enough I'll suffocate. In humans, breathing results in the lungs taking in about 5 L (~1.3 gal) of air per minute.

Breathing involves lots of other bodily activity. The brain monitors all sorts of changes in my body and breathing, including the pressure changes. If my blood oxygen level is low my brain will kick-start my breathing by making me breathe faster. But if my blood has enough oxygen I'll tend to stop. In response to oxygen deprivation, my blood vessels are likely to constrict, decreasing blood flow which results in dilation of my bronchioles.

Breath-holding is an attempt to hold the expansion of the lungs in check. This is a relatively common condition for divers. 40 litres

There are two stock exchanges: the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) and the NASDAQ Stock Market. The NYSE is an auction
system used by market-makers. A market-maker is an exchange member that acts as a dealer. The NASDAQ, on the other hand,
is an electronic exchange, and uses quoting systems that provide liquidity for securities.

An auction system is different than an electronic exchange. In an electronic exchange, a buyer and seller both log on
and use an electronic system to communicate. The dealer (or market-maker) uses the communication link to arbitrage
between bid and ask prices and can adjust the price at any time to maximize his profit. In an auction, traders have no
information on what another buyer or seller is willing to pay, and must make a bid or offer based on the information the
market-maker provides at that exact time. There are a couple of reasons the NYSE uses an auction system.

First, the NYSE is set up in a fashion to protect large investors by only allowing these users to access the exchange.
In order to be a member of the exchange, investors must pass the NYSE securities membership exam of passing
stress tests and financial qualifications. This keeps out unqualified investors as well as those with a bad reputation or
